<worksheet xml:id="week7-handout">
  <title>Week 7-8 Handout- Series Solution-Part 3</title>

    <introduction>
        <statement> <p>
        We will discuss the following topics related to <term> Series Solution</term>:
      <ul>
        <li> <p>Week 5: Power Series about Ordinary Points and Singular Points (Section 5.1-5.2) </p>   </li>
        <li> <p>Week 6-7: Orthogonal Functions (Section 12.1), Legendre Function (Section 5.3), Fourier Series (Section 12.2-12.4) </p> </li>
        <li>  <p> Week 7-Week 8: Boundary Value Problems in Rectangular Coordinates (13.1-13.5)</p></li>

      </ul>  </p>
        </statement>
    </introduction>
    <definition xml:id="def-complex">
      <statement>
        <p><ol>
          <li> <p>  <m>i</m> is the imaginary unit defined by <m>i^2=-1.</m>      </p></li>
          <li> <p> For <m>x</m> a real number, Euler's formula 
            <md xml:id="eq-euler" number="yes">
              e^{ix}=\cos x+i\sin x \mbox{ gives } e^{-ix}=\cos x-i\sin x. </md>   </p></li>
          <li> <p>  A <term>complex number</term> is a number <m>z=a+ib,</m> where <m>a</m> 
            and <m>b</m> are real numbers. The number <m>\bar{z}=a-ib</m> is called 
            the <term> conjugate</term> of <m>z.</m>     </p>  </li>
        </ol>          
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <statement>
        <p>From <xref ref="eq-euler"/>, we can derive
          <md xml:id="eq-cossin" number="yes"> 
            \cos x=\frac{e^{ix}+e^{-ix}}{2}\mbox{ and }\sin x=\frac{e^{ix}-e^{-ix}}{2i} </md>
            Then using <xref ref="eq-cossin"/> to replace <m>\cos\frac{n\pi x}{p}</m> and 
            <m>\sin \frac{n\pi x}{p}</m> in the defintion of Fourier Series.           
        </p>
      </statement>
    </remark> 
    <definition xml:id="def-complex-fourier">
      <title>Complex Fourier Series</title>
        <statement>
        <p>The <term>complex Fourier series</term> of function <m>f</m> defined on an interval <m>(-p,p)</m> 
          is given by 
          <md>
            <mrow xml:id="eq-complex-fourier" number="yes">
              f(x)\amp =\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}c_n e^{in\pi x/p} </mrow>
            <mrow>\mbox{where }c_n \amp = \frac{1}{2p}\int_{-p}^p f(x)e^{-in\pi x/p}dx, n=0,\pm 1,\pm 2,\ldots</mrow>
          </md>
          If <m>f(x)</m> is a periodic function and the <term>fundamental period</term> of <m>f</m> is <m>T=2p,</m>
           then <xref ref="eq-complex-fourier"/> becomes <m>\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}c_ne^{in\omega x},</m>
           where <m>\omega=\frac{2\pi}{T}</m> is called <term>fundamental angular frequency</term> and 
           <m>c_n</m> is called <term>frequency spectrum</term> of <m>f.</m>         
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the complex Fourier series of <m>f</m> on the given interval 
          <md>
            f(x)=\left\{\begin{array}{ll}-1\amp -2\lt x\lt 0\cr 1\amp 1, 0\lt x\lt 2.\end{array}\right\}
          </md>
          <ol>
            <li> <p> Graph the periodic expansion of <m>f.</m> </p>      </li>
            <li>  <p>   Graph Frequency spectrum of <m>f.</m>        </p></li>
            <li> <p> Sketch the graph of partial sum for <m>n=3, 6, 8, 10.</m>      </p>    </li>
          </ol>         
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="def-2nd-PDE">
      <title>Linear Partial Differential Equation</title>
      
      
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>u</m> denote the dependent variable and <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> 
          independent variables, the general form of a <term>linear second-order partial differential equations</term>
           is given by 
           <md xml:id="linear-2pde" number="yes">
            A\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}+B\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x\partial y}+C\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2}+D\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}+E\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}+Fu=G,
           </md>
           where the coefficients <m>A, B, \ldots, G</m> are constants or functions of <m>x</m> and <m>y.</m>
            When <m>G(x,y)=0</m>, <xref ref="linear-2pde"/> is said to be <term>homogeneous</term>; 
              otherwise, it is <term>nonhomogeneous.</term>    
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition xml:id="def-sep-var">
      <title>Separation of Variables</title>
       <statement><p>
          While seeking a particular solution of a differential equation in which 
          the independent variable are <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, we assume that this 
          particular solution is in the form of <term>product</term> of a function of <m>x</m>
           and a function of <m>y</m>:
           <md>
            u(x,y)=X(x)Y(y).
           </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Use Separation of Variables to solve 
          <md>\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}+4\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x\partial y}
            +\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2}=0.</md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-superposition">
      <title>Superposition Principle</title>   
      <statement>
        <p>If <m>u_1, u_2, \ldots, u_k</m> are solutions of a homogeneous linear PDE, 
          then the linear combination 
          <md> u=c_1u_1+c_2u_2+\cdots+c_ku_k,</md> 
          is also a solution, where <m>c_i, i=1,2,\ldots, k, </m> are constants.         
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <remark>
      Many other approaches are also based on the above theorem, 
      for example, power series, Fourier series, etc. 
      <md>u=\sum_{k=1}^\infty c_ku_k.</md>
      <ul>
        <li> <p> In power series, what is <m>u_k</m>? </p>   </li>
        <li> <p> In Fourier series, what is <m>u_k</m>?   </p> </li>
      </ul>
    </remark>
    <definition xml:id="def-classification-2nd-pdes">
      <title>Classification of linear 2nd-order PDEs</title>     
      <statement>
        <p> The linear 2nd order PDE:
          <md> A\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}+B\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x\partial y}+C\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2}
            +D\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}+E\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}+Fu=G,</md>
          is said to be 
          <ul>
            <li><p> <term>hyperbolic</term> if <m>B^2-4AC\gt 0,</m>      </p></li>
            <li><p> <term>parabolic</term> if <m>B^2-4AC=0,</m>  </p>  </li>
            <li><p><term>elliptic</term> if <m>B^2-4AC\lt 0.</m>    </p> </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>Classify each of given PDEs as hyperbolic, parabolic, or elliptic.
          <ol>
            <li><p>  <m>3\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}-4\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x\partial y}-\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2}=0</m>   </p>     </li>
            <li><p> <m>\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}+\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x\partial y}=u</m>  </p>  </li>
            <li><p> <m>k\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}=\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}, k>0</m>     </p></li>
          </ol>        
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <remark>
      <statement>
        <p> Here, we focus on finding product solutions of the 2nd-order PDEs 
    and observe the relationship with Fourier series:
    <ol>
      <li><p> 1-D Heat Equation:
        <md xml:id="heat1d" number="yes">
          k\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}=\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}, k\gt 0
        </md> </p> </li>
      <li> <p>1D Wave Equation:
        <md xml:id="wave1d" number="yes">
          a^2\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}=\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial t^2}          
        </md> </p></li>
      <li><p> Laplace's Equation:
        <md xml:id="laplace-eq" number="yes">
          \nabla^2 u=0,          
        </md> 
        where
      <md>
        \nabla^2 u=\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}+
        \frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2} \textbf{(2D Laplacian)},
      </md>      or
      <md>
        \nabla^2 u=\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}+\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2}+
        \frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial z^2}  \textbf{(3D Laplacian)}
      </md>     
       </p> </li>
    </ol>
          
        </p>
      </statement>
    </remark>
  <definition xml:id="def-heat">
    <title>1-D Heat Equation</title>
    
    
    <statement>
      <p> Consider a thin rod of length <m>L</m> with an initial temperature <m>f(x)</m> 
        throughout and whose ends are held at temperature zero for all time <m>t\gt 0.</m>
        <figure xml:id="fig-3d-rod-vertical-ellipse-left-half-ellipse-right">
      <caption>      A thin rod . </caption>
      <image>
      <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.7]
        \def\L{8}
        \def\yr{0.9}
        \def\xl{0.4}
        \def\xr{0.5}

        \draw[densely dashed, samples=160, domain=90:270, variable=\t]
          plot ({\xl*cos(\t)}, {\yr*sin(\t)});
        \draw[line width=0.9pt, samples=160, domain=-90:90, variable=\t]
          plot ({\xl*cos(\t)}, {\yr*sin(\t)});
        \draw[line width=0.9pt] (0,\yr) -- (\L,\yr);
        \draw[line width=0.9pt] (0,-\yr) -- (\L,-\yr);
        \draw[line width=1.1pt, samples=200, domain=-90:90, variable=\t]
          plot ({\L + \xr*cos(\t)}, {\yr*sin(\t)});
        \node[anchor=east] at (-0.25,0) {$u(0,t)$};
        \node[anchor=west] at (\L+\xr+0.35,0) {$u(L,t)$};
      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>
      The temperature <m>u(x,t)</m> in the rod is determined from the BVP:
      <md>
        <mrow> k\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}\amp= \frac{\partial u}{\partial t},0\lt x\lt L, t\gt 0 </mrow>
        <mrow> u(0,t)\amp= 0, t\gt 0  </mrow>
        <mrow> u(L,t)\amp= 0, t\gt 0 </mrow>
        <mrow> u(x,0)\amp= f(x),0\lt x\lt L  </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

</worksheet>

